{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488291"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"404"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/404"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.2,0.26,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52734"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/404"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38108"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"347"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44921"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52734"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 42-year-old woman presents with a six month history of a painless swelling on the upper part of her left neck. It has not changed in size and does not bother her unduly. On examination there is a well-defined, smooth surfaced, soft and non-tender 2 cm swelling on the anterior border of her sternocleidomastoid. No other masses can be felt and the rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. An ultrasound examination confirms the cystic nature of the swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","Repeat ultrasound in six months","Ultrasound guided aspiration and FNA","Aspiration and sclerosant injection","Formal excision"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has a painless swelling on the upper part of her left neck that has been present for six months and is confirmed by ultrasound to be a cystic swelling. The swelling is well-defined, smooth surfaced, soft and non-tender. There are no other masses felt and the rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. This is the classical presentation of a branchial cyst. Even though the condition arises from an embryonic abnormality, the cysts often do not appear until the third decade of life. Since the swelling does not bother the patient, the most appropriate plan of management in this case would be \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E, given the benign nature of this swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in six months\u003C/strong\u003E could be appropriate in some cases, but in this scenario, the swelling has already been present for six months and has not changed in size, which makes it unlikely that repeating the ultrasound in six months would provide any additional information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound-guided aspiration and FNA\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary in this case since the swelling is almost certainly a branchial cyst, as confirmed by ultrasound and there are no suspicious features to suggest malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Easpiration and sclerosant injection\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment option for certain types of cysts, it is not necessary in this case since the swelling is asymptomatic and not causing any discomfort or disfigurement to the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormal excision\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary in some cases, but it is not appropriate in this case unless the patient is worried about the swelling and wants it treated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Branchial cysts often do not become evident until the third decade of life."],"references":["GuidelineCentral. 2017. Evaluation of the neck mass in adults. Available at: https://www.guidelinecentral.com/guideline/6906/","Prosser JD, Myer CM. Branchial Cleft Anomalies and Thymic Cysts. Otolaryngol Clin N Am. 2015;48:1\u201314. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25442127/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38108"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"404"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38108"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T13:30:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T13:30:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"404"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52734"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4